405-01-013	API - Output Creation	
Output must be well formed, clear, and concise using the proper libraries.
Sensitive data such as credentials, passwords, security tokens, and API keys must not be returned in the URL or response.
API response payload schemas (API operations and methods (e.g. data model, output parameters, endpoints, authentication methods, etc.), including error responses, must be defined and enforced to avoid valuable information from being sent back to attackers.
N/A	5
405-01-014	API - Rate Limiting	
API must be implemented with Rate limiting policies for different API endpoints based on factors such as the type of request, user type, subscription plan, or API usage tiers.
Quotas must be enforced to limit the number of resources a single API call can consume.
Unauthenticated users must never be able to consume resources on the server unless the API is an open public API available to all users.  
If a request exceeds a resource limit the request must be rejected.
A maximum amount of the following resources required to satisfy a request must be appropriately set. This includes, but not limited to:
Execution Timeouts
Max allocable memory
Number of file descriptors
Number of processes
Request payload size
Number of requests per client/resources
Number of records per page to return in a single request response
